---
layout: page
title: About Tomoya Takano
---
I am Ph.D. student  at [Tohoku University](http://www.zisin.geophys.tohoku.ac.jp/){:target="_blank"} in Japan with experience in monitoring the crust using the seismic ambient noise.

My research is based on analysis of seismic data to understand dynamic processes of the Earth's structure.

I am particularly interested how the crust responds to stress perturbations (e.g. earthquakes, volcano deformations by magma pressure, tides, rainfall).

Currently, I investigate characteristics of stress sensitivities of seismic velocity changes by using tides and magma pressures. Since tides and magma pressures are estimated with high accuracy, seismic velocity changes caused by these loading provide a natural experiment to understand crustal dynamics. 

My study about seismic velocity changes related with volcanic activities can be found in the [EOS Spotlight](https://eos.org/research-spotlights/quiet-volcanic-activity-changes-speed-of-ambient-seismic-waves){:target="_blank"}.

